# Big O Notation (Most Important)

Big O notation represents the **worst-case time complexity** of an algorithm.  
It helps us understand how the runtime of an algorithm grows as the input size increases.

---

## Common Big O Complexities

| Complexity | Name         | Performance        |
|------------|--------------|--------------------|
| O(1)       | Constant     | Excellent          |
| O(log n)   | Logarithmic  | Very Fast          |
| O(n)       | Linear       | Good               |
| O(n log n) | Linearithmic | Efficient          |
| O(n²)      | Quadratic    | Slow for large n   |
| O(n³)      | Cubic        | Very Slow          |
| O(2ⁿ)      | Exponential  | Extremely Slow     |
| O(n!)      | Factorial    | Worst              |

---

### Notes:
- **O(1)**: Best possible complexity, independent of input size.  
- **O(log n)**: Common in divide-and-conquer algorithms like Binary Search.  
- **O(n)**: Typical for simple loops over input.  
- **O(n log n)**: Efficient sorting algorithms like Merge Sort and Quick Sort.  
- **O(n²)**: Nested loops, e.g., Bubble Sort.  
- **O(n³)**: Triple nested loops, often impractical for large inputs.  
- **O(2ⁿ)**: Recursive algorithms like naive Fibonacci.  
- **O(n!)**: Permutations, brute-force solutions — infeasible for large n.  

9. How to Analyze Time Complexity
Step-by-Step Method

Count loops → Determine how many times they run.

Check nesting → Nested loops multiply.

Look for recursion → Form recurrence relations.

Keep dominant term only → Ignore constants and smaller terms.

Example

Outer loop → n

Inner loop → n

Total operations → n × n = n²

Time Complexity = O(n²)

