# Time Complexity Growth Order

Understanding how different time complexities compare is crucial in Data Structures and Algorithms (DSA) interviews. Below is the order from **best (fastest)** to **worst (slowest)**:

---

## Complexity Order

**O(1) < O(log n) < O(n) < O(n log n) < O(n²) < O(n³) < O(2ⁿ) < O(n!)**

Think of it as:

**Constant → Logarithmic → Linear → Linearithmic → Quadratic → Cubic → Exponential → Factorial**

---

## Explanation

| Complexity | Name | Growth Behavior | Example Algorithms |
|------------|------|-----------------|--------------------|
| **O(1)** | Constant | Executes in the same time regardless of input size | Accessing array element, HashMap lookup |
| **O(log n)** | Logarithmic | Grows slowly, halves input each step | Binary Search |
| **O(n)** | Linear | Time grows directly with input size | Linear Search, Traversing an array |
| **O(n log n)** | Linearithmic | Slightly worse than linear, common in efficient sorting | Merge Sort, Quick Sort (average case) |
| **O(n²)** | Quadratic | Time grows with square of input size | Bubble Sort, Selection Sort |
| **O(n³)** | Cubic | Time grows with cube of input size | Matrix multiplication (naive) |
| **O(2ⁿ)** | Exponential | Doubles with each additional input | Recursive Fibonacci |
| **O(n!)** | Factorial | Explodes with permutations | Traveling Salesman (brute force), generating all permutations |

---

## Interview Notes

- **Acceptable in interviews:** O(1), O(log n), O(n), O(n log n)  
- **Borderline:** O(n²) (only for small inputs)  
- **Avoid:** O(n³), O(2ⁿ), O(n!) unless problem constraints are tiny  

---

## Quick Mnemonic

👉 **Constant → Log → Linear → Linearithmic → Quadratic → Cubic → Exponential → Factorial**

This sequence helps you quickly estimate whether an algorithm is practical for large inputs.

